Ex. No:  — Create Basic Visualizations (Line Plot, Bar Chart) using Matplotlib in Python

From the FDS lab concepts using Matplotlib

Aim

To create basic visualizations such as line plot and bar chart using Matplotlib in Python.

Theory

Data visualization helps to understand patterns and trends in data.
Matplotlib is a Python library used for creating graphs and charts.

Line Plot → Shows trends over data
Bar Chart → Compares values between categories


Line Plot:
•Shows the trend of a variable over another continuous variable.
•Useful for time series or sequential data.

Bar Chart:
•Represents categorical data with rectangular bars.
•Height of the bar indicates the value of the variable.
•Useful for comparing discrete categories.

Techniques Used
1.Importing Matplotlib
oimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt is used for plotting.

2.Creating Data
oUse Python lists or NumPy arrays for x and y values.

3.Line Plot
oplt.plot(x, y) creates a line plot.
oplt.title(), plt.xlabel(), plt.ylabel() add titles and labels.
oplt.grid() adds grid lines.

4.Bar Chart
oplt.bar(categories, values) creates a bar chart.
oColors and labels enhance readability.

5.Displaying Plots
oplt.show() renders the plots.

6.Interpretation
oIdentify trends, peaks, and comparisons from the plots.



Software / Tools Required
•Python 3.x
•Anaconda Distribution
•Jupyter Notebook / IDLE / Google Colab
•NumPy and Pandas Libraries



Program
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# Data for plotting
months = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May']
sales = [200, 250, 300, 280, 350]
# Line Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.plot(months, sales, marker='o', color='blue')
plt.title('Monthly Sales Trend')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Sales')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
# Bar Chart
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.bar(months, sales, color='green')
plt.title('Monthly Sales Comparison')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Sales')
plt.show()



Procedure
1.Start the program.
2.Import Matplotlib library.
3.Create a dataset for plotting.
4.Create a line plot using plt.plot().
5.Add title, labels, and grid.
6.Display the line plot.
7.Create a bar chart using plt.bar().
8.Add title and labels.
9.Display the bar chart.
10.Stop the program.


